Arthur Kirk ( 5 January 1878 -- 28 February 1958 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Melbourne in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Xu Jingzong ( 592 -- September 20 , 672 ) , courtesy name Yanzu , posthumously known as Duke Gong of Gaoyang , was a Chinese official who served as a chancellor in the Tang dynasty .
Major Radclyffe James Lindsay Bashford OBE ( 1881 - 1921 ) was at various times in his relatively brief life , an academic , journalist , novelist and soldier .
David Eugene Thompson ( 1854 - -1942 ) was an American diplomat .
Fred Storbeck ( 10 August 1889 -- 7 December 1970 ( aged 81 ) ) born in Pretoria was a South African Boer blacksmith , and amateur and professional heavyweight boxer of the 1910s and ' 20s , who won the South African heavyweight title , and British Empire heavyweight title .
Herbert Lange ( 29 September 1909 -- 20 April 1945 ) was an SS - Sturmbannführer ( major ) and the commandant of Chełmno extermination camp until April 1942 ; leader of the SS Special Detachment Lange conducting the extermination of Jews from the Łódź Ghetto .
Mikhail Fonin ( 1905 -- 1974 ) served as the eighth General Secretary of the Communist Party of the Turkmen SSR .
Robert Hunter Morris ( 1700 in Trenton , New Jersey -- 27 January 1764 in Shrewsbury , New Jersey ) , was a prominent governmental figure in Colonial Pennsylvania , serving as governor of Pennsylvania and Chief Justice of the New Jersey Supreme Court .
Nikolas Asimos ( Greek : Νικόλας Άσιμος ; 20 August 1949 -- 17 March 1988 ) was a Greek composer and singer .
Gustav Behrend ( January 10 , 1847 -- 1925 ) was a German dermatologist who was a native of Neustettin ( today- Szczecinek , Poland ) .
Hedwig Bollhagen ( 10 November 1907 -- 8 June 2001 ) was a leading German ceramicist influenced by the Bauhaus .
Noah Komla Dzobo ( died 2010 ) was an academic and religious leader .
Pompeo Cesura ( born c.1500 - -1571 ) , also known as Pompeo Dall'Aquila or Pompeo Aquilano , was an Italian painter and engraver .
William Dallimore ( 1871 -- 7 November 1959 ) was an English botanist who published a `` Handbook of Coniferae '' and who played an important role in the start and development of Bedgebury Pinetum .
Samuel Alexander OM ( 6 January 1859 -- 13 September 1938 ) was an Australian - born British philosopher .
Ryszard Świętochowski ( born September 17 , 1882 in Warsaw - 1941 in Auschwitz ) was a Polish politician , publicist and engineer .
Solomon Ettinger ( 1802 -- 1856 ) was a 19th - century Yiddish- and Hebrew - language playwright , poet and writer of songs and fables whose emblematic play Serkele has remained a classic of the Yiddish theatre .
Sotir Kuneshka ( 1912 - -1991 ) was an Albanian physicist and academic .
Imre Horváth ( 19 November 1901 -- 2 February 1958 ) was a Hungarian politician , who served as Minister of Foreign Affairs twice : in 1956 and after the Hungarian Revolution of 1956 until his death .
James Johnson Sweeney ( 1900 - -1986 ) was a curator , and writer about modern art . Sweeney graduated from Georgetown University in 1922 .
Florentia Sale ( née Wynch ; 13 August 1790 -- 6 July 1853 ) was an Englishwoman who travelled the world while married to her husband , Sir Robert Henry Sale , a British army officer .
Francis Egerton , 1st Earl of Ellesmere KG , PC ( 1 January 1800 -- 18 February 1857 ) , known as Lord Francis Leveson - Gower until 1833 , was a British politician , writer , traveller and patron of the arts .
Herbert Lionel Elvin ( 7 August 1905 in Buckhurst Hill -- 14 June 2005 in Cambridge ) was an eminent educationist .
Charles - François Daubigny ( 15 February 1817 -- 19 February 1878 ) was one of the painters of the Barbizon school , and is considered an important precursor of Impressionism .
Alessandro Melani ( 4 February 1639 -- 3 October 1703 ) was an Italian composer and the brother of composer Jacopo Melani , and castrato singer Atto Melani .
Louis Vico Žabkar ( 1914 - -1994 ) was an Egyptologist who published a number of academic works and who participated in the 1960s the UNESCO campaign to salvage the monuments threatened by the building of the Aswan Dam .
Ernest Trimingham ( 1880 - 1942 ) was an actor from the colony of Bermuda .
Sir Thomas Clere ( died 14 April 1545 ) was a successful poet at the court of Henry VIII . He is commemorated in several poems by Henry Howard , Earl of Surrey , with whom he had a very close friendship .
Harriet Isabel Ballintine ( December 23 1864 -- February 9 1951 ) was the athletic director at Vassar College from 1891 to 1930 and was a leader in the development of physical education for women .
Hussein Samatar ( Somali : Xuseen Samatar , Arabic : حسين ساماتار‎ ) ( 1964 -- 25 August 2013 ) was a Somali American politician , banker and community organizer .
During the periode 1323 - 1328 and at the Battle of Cassel , Jan Heem was one of the leaders of Bruges .
Chen Changxing or Ch'en Chang - hsing ( 1771 - -1853 ) was a 14th generation descendant and 6th generation master of the Chen Family and was an influential martial artist and teacher of taijiquan ( t'ai chi ch'uan ) .
Lawrence Kilburn ( sometimes Kilbrunn or Kilbourn ) ( 1720 - -1775 ) was a painter active in the colony of New York .
Vice Admiral Vincent Barkly Molteno CB ( 30 April 1872 -- 12 November 1952 ) was a Royal Navy officer during World War I. He fought and distinguished himself in the Battle of Jutland in April 1916 , commanding from the armoured cruiser HMS Warrior .
Geoffrey Beaumont ( 1903 - -1970 ) was an Anglican priest and monk of the Community of the Resurrection who was also a composer of popular songs and hymn tunes .
( William ) Denis Johnston ( 18 June 1901 -- 8 August 1984 ) was an Irish writer .
Henry J. Wilson ( born 1793 - died 1872 ) was a U.S. Army officer who served in five wars and countless conflicts .
Boško Perošević ( Serbian : Бошко Перошевић ; 17 September 1956 - -13 May 2000 ) was a Serbian politician and former Chairman of the Executive Council of Vojvodina .
Margaret Buckley ( née Goulding ) ( Irish : Maighréad Uí Bhuachalla ( née Ní Ghabhláin ) ) ( 1879 -- 24 July 1962 ) was an Irish republican and leader of Sinn Féin from 1937 to 1950 .
Barys Rahula ( Belarusian : Барыс Рагуля , Boris Ragula , 1 January 1920 -- 22 April 2005 ) was a Belarusian military commander serving with the Biełaruskaja Krajovaja Abarona ( BKA ) during World War II ; the military arm of the pro - Nazi Belarusian Central Rada .
Albert Modley ( 1901 , in Liverpool , Lancashire -- 23 February 1979 , in Morecambe , Lancashire ) was a variety entertainer and comedian .
Philip of Majorca ( Catalan : Felip ; 1288 - -1343 ) was an infante and a Franciscan who served as regent of the Kingdom of Majorca between 1324 and 1329 .
Over the next few years , Ardashir I further expanded his new empire , and must have driven out or defeated Vologases VI soon after 228 .
Cassone della Torre ( or Casso , Cassono , Castone , Gastone ) , also called Mosca ( died 20 August 1318 ) was an Italian medieval condottiero and feudal lord .
On 1 November 1899 , while meeting with several other compatriots , Aghbiur Serob had his pipe poisoned by a fellow Armenian known as `` Avé '' who had been bribed by Kurdish brigands .
John Keppock ( died 1404 ) was an Irish judge who held the offices of Lord Chief Justice of Ireland and Chief Baron of the Irish Exchequer .
Ing . Pablo Cagnasso Sr . ( 15 February 1908 -- 1988 ) was an Argentinian civil engineer and sport shooter who was a member of the Argentinean Olympic team on several occasions as well as in many World Cups and Pan American Games .
Les Rennie ( 21 September 1908 -- 25 September 1983 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Essendon in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Barbara Jane Harrison GC ( 24 May 1945 -- 8 April 1968 ) , typically known as Jane Harrison , was a British air stewardess .
George Hosmer ( born in Farmington , Connecticut , 30 August 1781 ; died in Chicago , Illinois , 6 March 1861 ) was a U.S. lawyer and politician .
Joseph Rowbotham ( 8 July 1831 -- 22 December 1899 ) was an English first - class cricketer , who played six matches for Yorkshire County Cricket Club , in their pre - county incarnation from 1861 and 1862 , and 94 for them as a full county club from 1863 to 1876 .
André Mathilde Édouard Parengh ( 12 November 1926 -- 2 September 2011 ) , better known under the pseudonym Tony Corsari , was a Belgian TV show host and presenter .
Geraldine McEwan ( born Geraldine McKeown ; 9 May 1932 -- 30 January 2015 ) was an English actress who had a long career in theatre , television and film .
Chester Melvin Vaniman ( 1866 - 1912 ) was an American photographer , adventurer and businessman who specialized in panoramic images taken from height and was nicknamed the `` Acrobatic Photographer . ''
Kristo Das Pal ( Bengali : কৃষ্ণদাস পাল ) ( 1838 -- 24 July 1884 ) , was an Indian journalist , orator and the editor of Hindoo Patriot .
Pieter Hendrik Kritzinger ( 1870 , Port Elizabeth -- 1930 , Cradock , Eastern Cape ) , was a Boer general and guerrilla commander during the Second Boer War .
Johann Heinrich Hartmann Bätz ( 1 January 1709 -- 13 December 1770 ) was a German - Dutch organ builder .
Stephen Spargo ( 29 December 1903 -- 1972 ) was an English professional association footballer who played as a half back .
Reuven Barkat ( Hebrew : ראובן ברקת‎ , born Reuven Borstein 25 October 1906 -- 5 April 1972 ) was an Israeli politician who served as a member of the Knesset for the Alignment and the Labor Party from 1965 until his death in 1972 .
Esfandiar Ahmadieh ( Persian : اسفندیار احمدیه‎‎ ; 1929 - -2012 ) was an Iranian animation film director .
Maria Angela Ardinghelli ( 1730 - -1825 ) was an Italian translator , mathematician , physicist and noble , mostly known as the Italian translator of the works of Stephen Hales , a Newtonian physiologist .
William Valentine Black ( 21 February 1832 -- 1 April 1927 ) was a nineteenth - century Utah pioneer , and one of the early settlers of Manti , Spring City , Rockville , and Deseret , Utah .
Peter Johannes Rutten ( 9 December 1864 , Afferden ( Limburg ) - 3 September 1953 , Wanssum ) was a Dutch politician .
Ravi Datt Mehta ( 1955 -- 7 July 2008 ) was a brigadier in the Indian army .
Leo Schaya ( 1916 - -1985 ) was a Swiss author and scholar whose works focused on the Sufi tradition , the Kabbalah , and the Traditionalist School .
Henry Glemham ( Glenham ) ( c.1603- 17 January 1670 ) was an English royalist churchman , Dean of Bristol and Bishop of St Asaph .
Colonel Robert Peel Dawson ( 1818 -- 2 September 1877 ) was an Irish Member of the House of Commons at Westminster .
Shankarrao Salvi ( 15 July 1931 -- 15 February 2007 ) was an Indian Kabaddi player , coach and administrator .
Alexander de Stavenby ( or Alexander of Stainsby ; died 26 December 1238 ) was a medieval Bishop of Coventry and Lichfield .
Donald Alaster Macdonald ( 6 June 1859 -- 23 November 1932 ) was an Australian journalist and nature writer .
Agnes Gordon ( 1906 - -1967 ) was a Canadian bridge player .
Patrick Milne ( c. 1755 - -16 May 1820 ) was a Scottish landowner , businessman and politician .
Marcelle Meyer ( French : ( mɛjɛʁ ) ; 22 May 1897 -- 17 November 1958 ) was a French pianist .
Caridad Hierrezuelo ( El Caney , 1924 -- Havana , 6 February 2009 ) was a Cuban popular singer .
Tim Souster ( 29 January 1943 -- 1 March 1994 ) was a British composer and writer on music , best known for his electronic music output ( Jack 1994 ) .
Sulpicia Dryantilla ( died 260 ) was the wife of Regalianus , Roman usurper against Gallienus .
Erna Steinberg ( also Erna Boeck ; 30 June 1911 -- 21 April 2001 ) was a German track and field athlete who specialised in sprinting events .
Harry C. Claiborne ( January 1859 - 1918 ) was an American lighthouse keeper .
Ruaidrí ua Canannáin ( died 30 November 950 ) was king of the Cenél Conaill , and according to some sources , High King of Ireland .
Count Pál Széchenyi de Sárvár - Felsővidék ( 6 November 1838 -- 28 October 1901 ) was a Hungarian politician , who served as Minister of Agriculture , Industry and Trade between 1882 and 1889 .
Guy Hance ( 1933 -- 8 January 2008 ) was a deputy of Front National at the Parliament of Brussels from 1999 to 2004 and from October 2006 to January 2008 .
Gerald Wickremesooriya ( Sinhalese : ජෙරල්ඩ් වික්‍රමසූරිය ; 1920 -- 9 January 2006 ) is the founder of the Sooriya Record label that produced many popular hits from late 1960 's to the early 1980s .
Thomas Preston , 1st Viscount Tara ( 1585 - -1655 ) was an Irish soldier of the 17th century .
Christian Stub ( 1693 -- 18 December 1736 ) was a Norwegian jurist , law historian and civil servant .
Karol Popiel ( 28 October 1887 , Rzochów - 6 June 1977 , Rome ) was a Polish politician of Christian democracy faction and writer .
Owen Price ( died 25 November 1671 ) was a Welsh schoolmaster and writer .
Cathal mac Áedo Flaind Chathrach ( died 627 ) was a King of Cashel in Munster from the Glendamnach sept of the Eoganachta .
Carlo Hintermann ( 2 April 1923 -- 7 January 1988 ) was an Italian film , television and stage actor and voice actor .
Robert Hopton ( died 1638 ) was an English landowner and politician who sat in the House of Commons in two parliaments between 1604 and 1622 .
Brigadier General Thomas Stanwix ( 1670 -- 14 March 1725 ) was a British Army officer , politician and Governor of Gibraltar .
Paul Droubay ( 11 September 1926 - 14 January 2013 ) was an American radio broadcaster located in Utah .
Don Diego de Guevara ( c. 1450 - -1520 ) was a Spanish courtier and ambassador who served four , possibly five , successive Dukes of Burgundy , spanning the Valois and Habsburg dynasties , mostly in the Low Countries .
Walter Colmes ( 1917 - -1988 ) was an American film director and producer sometimes billed as Walter S. Colmes .
Helen Alexander ( 1654 -- March 1729 ) was a heroine of the Scottish Covenanters in the unequal struggle between the adherents of ancient Presbyterianism and prelacy .
Lester Beall ( 1903 - -1969 ) was an American graphic designer notable as a leading proponent of modernist graphic design in the United States .
Sir Hugh de Paduinan ( 1140 -- 1189 ) was a Scoto - Norman baron , Knight Templar and progenitor of the Clan Houston .
George Victor Du Noyer ( 1817 -- 3 January 1869 ) was an Irish painter , geologist and antiquary of Huguenot descent .
Renée Richard ( 1930 - -31 March 2014 ) was a renowned French cheesemonger in Lyon and the proprietor of La Mère Richard at Les Halles , 102 Cours Lafayette in Lyons .
Arthur William Gebaur Jr. ( February 22 , 1919 - -Missing in Action and presumed dead in Korean War on August 29 , 1952 ) was awarded the Distinguished Service Cross for action in the war .
Maud Humphrey ( March 30 , 1868 -- 1940 ) was a commercial illustrator , water colorist , and suffragette from the United States .
Thomas Raffles Davison ARIBA ( 1853 - 5 May 1937 ) was an English architectural illustrator and journalist of the late 19th and early 20th centuries .
Róbert Tábori ( November 10 , 1855 - -1906 ) was a Hungarian author born at Almas and educated in Baja , Budapest , and Vienna .
Isaac Abendana ( ca . 1640 -- 1699 ) was the younger brother of Jacob Abendana , and became hakam of the Spanish Portuguese Synagogue in London after his brother died .
Phil Hosking ( 4 May 1894 - 6 August 1949 ) was a former Australian rules footballer who played with Melbourne in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Liu Guangdi ( Chinese : 刘光第 ; ~1859 - 1898 ) was a Chinese government minister during the late Qing dynasty .
Rudolf Redlinghofer ( 31 October 1900 -- 11 January 1940 ) was an Austrian conscientious objector and victim of the Nazi regime .
Sir Thomas Lyttelton , 1st Baronet ( 1593 -- 22 February 1650 ) was a Royalist officer from the Lyttelton family during the English Civil War .
Jorge Ginarte ( 1940 -- 7 June 2010 ) was an Argentine professional football player and coach .
Bryan Cowgill ( 27 May 1927 -- 14 July 2008 ) was a British television executive .
John Cropper ( 1797 - -1876 ) was a British philanthropist and abolitionist .
Lieutenant Colonel Qazi Altaf Hussain ( 1920 - -1999 ) was an man who served in the British Indian Army later taking up a position in the Army of Pakistan .
Therese Krones ( 7 October 1801 -- 28 December 1830 ) was an Austrian actress of much ability and grace in comic parts .
Tom Clayton ( c. 1880 -- 24 March 1909 ) was an Australian jockey of the early 19th century .
Max Vorspan ( died June 2002 ) was an American rabbi , professor , historian , and administrator at the American Jewish University , and leader in the Los Angeles Jewish community .
Oran Wendle Eagleson ( 1910 - -1997 ) was the Callaway Professor of Psychology at Spelman College , Atlanta .
Samuel Schulman ( 14 February 1864 -- 2 November 1955 ) was an American rabbi .
Vishnudevananda Saraswati ( 31 December 1927 -- 9 November 1993 ) was a disciple of Sivananda Saraswati , and founder of the International Sivananda Yoga Vedanta Centres and Ashrams .
Robert the Lotharingian ( also known as Robert de Losinga and Robert of Lorraine ; died 26 June 1095 ) was a priest who became Bishop of Hereford following the Norman Conquest of England .
Eugene Abeshaus ( also spelled Evgeny Abezgauz , Евгений Абезгауз in Russian ; 1939 - -2008 ) was a Jewish artist who worked in Russia ( then USSR ) and Israel .
Benedetto Ghirlandaio ( 1458 - -1497 ) was an Italian ( Florentine ) painter .
Sir Thomas Skipwith , 1st Baronet ( ca . 1620 -- 2 June 1694 ) was an English politician who sat in the House of Commons in 1659 and 1660 .
Chauncey Yellow Robe ( `` Kills in the Woods '' ) ( Canowicakte ) ( 1867 - -1930 ) was an educator , lecturer and Native American activist .
Peggy Webling ( 1 January 1871 -- 27 June 1949 ) was a British playwright , novelist and poet .
John B. Timberlake ( 1777 - -1828 ) was a protagonist in the American political scandal known as the Petticoat affair .
Ernest Trumpp ( 13 March 1828 -- 5 April 1885 ) was a German philologist and missionary to Sindh Province , Punjab Province , and Peshawar -- all part of then - British India before the independence of Pakistan in 1947 .
Heinrich Leo ( 17 March 1799 -- 24 April 1878 ) was a Prussian historian born in Rudolstadt , his father being chaplain to the garrison there .
Bogusław Radoszewski ( c. 1577 - -1638 ) of Oksza coat of arms was a Polish noble and Roman Catholic priest .
Sir Thomas Widdrington SL ( died 13 May 1664 ) was an English judge and politician who sat in the House of Commons at various times between 1640 and 1664 .
Samir Chanda ( 1957 -- 18 August 2011 ) was an Indian art director and production designer across Indian cinema , including Hindi , Bengali , Malayalam and Tamil , most known for his work in films like Yodha ( 1992 ) , Dil Se ..
Sir Edward Hain ( December 1851 -- 20 September 1917 ) was a leading shipping owner in Cornwall , England , and a politician who represented St Ives as a Liberal Unionist from 1900 to 1904 , and as a Liberal from 1904 to 1906 .
Liang Chongyi ( 梁崇義 ) ( died 781 ) was a general of the Chinese dynasty Tang Dynasty .
George Edwin Butler ( 1868 - -1941 ) was an American lawyer and an author of research studies and works , the most notable of which is his book The Croatan Indians of Sampson County , North Carolina .
Abd al - Majid ibn Abdun , or in full Abu Mohammed Abd al - Majid ibn Abdun al - Yaburi عبد المجيد بن عبدون اليابري(c . 1050- 1135 , died in Évora ) was a poet from Al - Andalus .
Othon de la Roche , also Otho de la Roche , ( died before 1234 ) was a Burgundian nobleman from the castle of La Roche - sur - l'Ognon .
Francis Smallman ( 1565 -- 7 September 1633 ) was an English politician who sat in the House of Commons in 1621 and 1626 .
Isidore Jacques Eggermont ( 15 May 1844 -- 16 April 1923 ) was a Belgian diplomat , who was also active as a photographer and writer in North Africa and Asia .
Curt von Gottberg ( 11 February 1896 -- 31 May 1945 ) was a Nazi official and military commander .
Leo Jansen ( 30 April 1930 , The Hague - 20 December 1980 ) was a Dutch artist known for his portraits .
Wan Shenzi ( simplified Chinese : 万慎子 ; traditional Chinese : 萬慎子 ; pinyin : Wàn Shènzǐ ; 1856 - -1923 ) , born in Luzhou , Sichuan , was one of the most famous Chinese couplet writers in the late Qing Dynasty .
Benedykta Mackieło ( 1 May 1893 - 1 January 2007 ) was probably the oldest of Poles .
Ulrika Åberg ( 1771 - -1852 ) was a Swedish ballerina , one of the first native ballet dancers in the Royal Swedish Ballet , which was in the beginning dominated by foreign dancers .
Lea Deutsch ( Croatian pronunciation : ( lêa dâjtʃ ) ; 18 March 1927 -- May 1943 ) was a Croatian Jewish child actress who died during the Holocaust .
Giovanni Frattini ( 8 January 1852 -- 21 July 1925 ) was an Italian mathematician , noted for his contributions to group theory .
Tarenorerer , also known as Walyer ( 1800 -- 5 June 1831 ) , was a rebel leader of the Indigenous Australians in Tasmania .
Richard de Fournival or Richart de Fornival ( 1201 -- ? 1260 ) was a medieval philosopher and trouvère perhaps best known for the Bestiaire d'amour ( `` The Bestiary of Love '' ) .
Adolf Naef ( 1 May 1883 - 11 May 1949 ) was a Swiss zoologist and palaeontologist who worked on cephalopods and systematics .
John Edwin Fulton ( 1869 - -1945 ) was a Seventh - day Adventist minister , missionary , and administrator .
Charles Étienne Raymond Victor de Verninac ( 19 November 1803 -- 22 May 1834 ) was a minor French diplomat , nephew of the painter Eugène Delacroix ( 1798 - -1863 ) .
Enrique Dawi ( 1927 - 1988 ) was an Argentine film director and screenplay writer .
John MacGillivray ( 18 December 1821 -- 6 June 1867 ) was a Scottish - naturalist , active in Australia between 1842 and 1867 .
Elisabeth Charlotta Karsten , married surname Kachanoff ( 1789 - -1856 ) , was a Swedish painter .
Les Tremayne ( 16 April 1913 -- 19 December 2003 ) was a radio , film and television actor .
Sir Francis Norie - Miller , 1st Baronet ( 11 March 1859 -- 4 July 1947 ) was a British insurance company manager director .
Hans Caspar Hirzel ( 21 March 1725 - 18 February 1803 ) , also known or spelt as - Herzil John Caspar , Kaspar Hirzel , Johann Kasper Herzel , or John Kaspar Hirzel - , was an eminent Swiss physician and writer on rural economy .
Imam Mohamad Jawad Chirri ( Arabic : محمد جواد شيري‎ ) was the founder and was director of the Islamic Center of America until his death in 1994 in Dearborn , Michigan , USA .
Sir Edmund Peirce or Pierse ( died 1667 ) , of Greenwich , Kent and Holborn , Middlesex , was an English politician .
Max Horder ( 23 March 1923 -- 30 April 1965 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Collingwood in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Li Guangbi ( 李光弼 ) ( 708 -- August 15 , 764 ) , formally Prince Wumu of Linhuai ( 臨淮武穆王 ) , was a general of the Chinese dynasty Tang Dynasty , of ethnic Khitan ancestry , who was instrumental in Tang 's suppression of the Anshi Rebellion .
William Jenkyn ( 1613 - -1685 ) was an English clergyman , imprisoned during the Interregnum for his part in the `` presbyterian plot '' of Christopher Love , ejected minister in 1662 , and imprisoned at the end of his life for nonconformity .
Alan Conway ( 1934 -- 5 December 1998 ) was an English conman , best known for impersonating film director Stanley Kubrick .
Turkey Tolson Tjupurrula ( sometimes just Turkey Tolson ; c. 1938 -- 10 August 2001 ) was a Pintupi - speaking Indigenous artist from Australia 's Western Desert region .
Allen Raine was the pseudonym of the Welsh novelist Anne Adaliza Beynon Puddicombe ( 6 October 1836 -- 21 June 1908 ) .
Juliusz Bogdan Deczkowski `` Laudański '' ( 20 April 1924 in Bydgoszcz -- 22 June 1998 in Ciechocinek ) was a noted Polish soldier during World War II , and later an engineer and inventor , as well as writer .
Jean Gloria Edith Puketapu or Jean Puketapu - Waiwai QSO ( 26 July 1931 -- 31 July 2012 ) was a Ngāi Tūhoe Māori language activist and co - founder of the first kōhanga reo .
Sir Albanis Beaumont ( ca . 1755 - -1812 ) draughtsman , aquatint engraver , and landscape painter , was born in Piedmont , but naturalised in England .
Sir Creswell Levinz ( 1627 - -1701 ) , judge , was the second son of William Levinz , the elder , of Evenley , Northamptonshire , by Mary , second daughter of Richard Creswell of Purston in the same county .
Stephen Hudson ( 1868 -- 29 October 1944 ) is a pseudonym of the British novelist and translator Sydney Schiff , whose work was published in the 1910s , ' 20s , and ' 30s .
Sir Aston Cockayne , 1st Baronet ( 1608 - -1684 ) was , in his day , a well - known Cavalier and a minor literary figure , now best remembered as a friend of Philip Massinger , John Fletcher , Michael Drayton , Richard Brome , Thomas Randolph , and other writers of his generation .
Kent Kane Parrot ( c. 1882 - March 11 , 1956 ) was an American political figure and attorney who was considered the `` boss '' of municipal politics in Los Angeles , California , in the 1920s .
Captain Elizur Holyoke ( c.1618 - -1676 ) of Springfield , Massachusetts was the namesake of the mountain , Mount Holyoke , and ( indirectly ) , of the city of Holyoke , Massachusetts .
Carl Martin Reinthaler ( 13 October 1822 -- 13 February 1896 ) was a German organist , conductor and composer .
Eliyahu Moyal ( Hebrew : אליהו מויאל‎ , born 2 August 1920 , died 6 September 1991 ) was an Israeli politician who served as a member of the Knesset for the Alignment between 1974 and 1981 .
Nicholas Tichborne ( b. at Hartley Mauditt , Hampshire ; executed at Tyburn , London , 24 August 1601 ) was an English Roman Catholic layman , a recusant and Catholic martyr .
Guillelma de Rosers ( fl . 1235 - -1265 ) , also spelled Guilleuma , Guillielma , Guilielma , or Guilhelma , was a Provençal trobairitz of the mid - thirteenth century , one of the last known trobairitz .
Rafael Bertrand ( 20 August 1917 -- 5 October 1982 ) was a Cuban film actor who worked for many years in the Mexican film industry .
George Smits ( Antwerp , 1944 - -1997 ) , aka ' Toet ' , was a Belgian visual artist , experimental musician and inventor of experimental musical instruments .
Rachel Gurney ( 5 March 1920 -- 24 November 2001 ) was an English actress .
Peter Drelincourt ( 22 July 1644 in Paris -- 7 March 1722 in Armagh ) , was Dean of Armagh .
Arnold Chernushevich ( Russian : Арнольд Петрович Чернушевич , 15 January 1933 -- 2 September 1991 ) was a Soviet Olympic fencer .
James Terry White ( 3 July 1845 in Newburyport , Massachusetts -- 3 April 1920 in Manhattan , New York ) was an American publisher and poet .
Johnson Chesnut Whittaker ( 1858 - -1931 ) was one of the first black men to win an appointment to the United States Military Academy at West Point .
Gaioz Devdariani ( Georgian : გაიოზ დევდარიანი ) ( February 2 , 1901 -- 1938 ) was a prominent Georgian revolutionary , Soviet politician , member of the Georgian National Academy of Sciences and a victim of the Great Purge of 1937 .
Jacobs Pier Pander ( 20 June 1864 -- 6 September 1919 ) was a Dutch sculptor and designer of medals .
Sir Robert Palk , 1st Baronet ( December 1717 -- 29 April 1798 ) of Haldon House in the parish of Kenn , in Devon , England , was an officer of the British East India Company who served as Governor of the Madras Presidency .
Alexander Watt Williamson ( 1849 - 1928 ) in 1874 was the first person to receive a degree from a New Zealand University .
Alice de la Roche , Lady of Beirut , Regent of Beirut ( died 1282 ) was the wife of John II of Ibelin , Lord of Beirut , in the Kingdom of Jerusalem .
Jens Aars ( 1 October 1779 -- 27 March 1834 ) was a Norwegian priest and Member of Parliament .
John Ashburnham , 2nd Earl of Ashburnham , PC ( 30 October 1724 -- 8 April 1812 ) , styled Viscount St Asaph from 1730 to 1737 , was a British peer and courtier .
Christopher Bernevall , or Barnewall ( 1370 - -1446 ) was an Irish politician and judge who held the offices of Vice - Treasurer of Ireland and Lord Chief Justice of Ireland .
Hank Bagby ( died 11 December 1993 ) was originally a singer around Denver in the mid-1940s .
Félix Boisselier `` the elder '' ( 13 April 1776 -- 12 January 1811 ) was a French historical painter .
Gabriel Marselis ( c. 1575 -- 16 July 1643 , Hamburg ) was a Dutch merchant .
Ahmat Acyl ( 1944 - -1982 ) was a Chadian Arab insurgent leader during the Chadian Civil War .
Olaus Andreas Grøndahl ( 4 November 1847 -- 31 December 1923 ) was a Norwegian conductor , singing teacher and composer .
Michael Lort ( 1725 - -1790 ) was a Welsh clergyman , academic and antiquary .
Theodor Granderath ( 19 June 1839 , Giesenkirchen , Rhine Province -- 19 March 1902 , Valkenburg , Netherlands ) was a German Jesuit scholar .
Mal Morgan was an Australian poet , prominent in the Melbourne poetry scene from the 1970s through to his death in 1999 .
Robert Scawen ( 1602 - -1670 ) was an English politician who sat in the House of Commons at various times between 1640 and 1670 .
Luc Wallays ( 7 August 1961 -- 5 March 2013 ) was a Belgian professional racing cyclist .
Velasquita Ramírez ( pronunciation : ( βelaskita ramireθ ) ) ( d. c. 1035 ) was Queen consort of León as the first wife of King Bermudo II and mother of infanta Cristina Bermúdez , wife of Ordoño Ramírez .
John Wesley Neville Martin ( 1916 - 17 April 1966 ) was a Northern Irish politician who served as a member of the Parliament of Northern Ireland for the Ulster Unionist Party .
Marcus Valerius Probus ( c. 20/30 -- 105 AD ) of Berytus , was a Roman grammarian and critic , who flourished during Nero 's reign .
Sir Charles Marcus Mander , 3rd Baronet ( 22 September 1921 -- 9 August 2006 ) was an industrialist , property developer , landowner and farmer .
Haile Fida languished in prison for some time , until at last he was executed ; the circumstances of his death are unclear , but Andargachew Tiruneh states that he was killed two years after his arrest , in 1979 .
Sir John Rigby Hale ( 17 September 1923 -- 12 August 1999 ) was a British historian and translator , best known for his Renaissance studies .
Görvel Fadersdotter ( Sparre ) ( 1509 or 1517 -- 20 April 1605 ) , was a Danish - Swedish ( Scanian ) landholder and county administrator .
Bertrand Hallward ( 24 May 1901 -- 17 November 2003 ) was the first Vice - Chancellor of the University of Nottingham .
Giovanni Battista Conforti ( fl . 1550 - -1570 ) was an Italian composer , born either in Bologna or Parma .
Joseph Nigg ( 13 October 1782 -- 19 September 1863 ) was an Austrian painter , with painting on porcelain a specialty .
Chandler Brossard ( July 18 , 1922 -- August 29 , 1993 ) was an American novelist , writer , editor , and teacher .
Giorgi I Dadiani ( Georgian : გიორგი I დადიანი ; died 1323 ) was a member of the House of Dadiani and eristavi ( `` duke '' ) of Odishi in western Georgia from the late 13th century until his death .
Sir Anthony Fitzherbert ( 1470 -- 27 May 1538 ) was an English judge , scholar and legal author , particularly known for his treatise on English law , New Natura Brevium ( 1534 ) .
Delavan Leonard Pierson ( 1867 - 1952 ) , son of Arthur Tappan Pierson , was an American Presbyterian pastor , Christian leader , and writer .
Abdul Sattar Baloch or Ostaad Abdul Sattar Baloch ( استاد عبدالستار بلوچ:Balochi ) ( c. 1951 - -2006 ) was a Baloch nationalist vocalist and musician .
Ignacio Mariano Martinez de Galinsoga ( 1766 Huesca , Granada - 1797 ) , physician to the Spanish Queen consort Maria Luisa of Parma , founder and director of the Real Jardín Botánico de Madrid , and founder of the Spanish Real Academia Nacional de Medicina .
Thomas Henry Mahy ( 5 October 1862 -- 21 April 1936 ) wrote Dires et Pensées du Courtil Poussin , a regular column in Guernésiais in La Gazette Officielle de Guernesey , from 1916 .
Erich Jantsch ( 8 January 1929 -- 12 December 1980 ) was an Austrian - born American astrophysicist , engineer , educator , author , consultant and futurist , especially known for his work in the social systems design movement in Europe in the 1970s .
Samuel Isaac Joseph Schereschewsky ( pronounced skĕr - ĕs - kūs'kĭ Chinese : 施約瑟 ; 6 May 1831 -- 15 October 1906 ) , also known as Joseph Schereschewsky , was the Anglican Bishop of Shanghai , China , from 1877 to 1884 .
Barna Buza ( 1 January 1873 -- 2 May 1944 ) was a Hungarian politician and jurist , who served as Minister of Agriculture from 1918 to 1919 and as interim Minister of Justice for few days in 1918 .
Thomas Inch ( 27 December 1881 in Scarborough , England -- 12 December 1963 ) held the titles of Britain 's Strongest Youth and Britain 's Strongest Man .
Rhygyfarch or Rhigyfarch ( in contemporary late Old Welsh orthography Ricemarch , 1057 - -1099 ) , eldest son of Sulien , whom he may have succeeded in 1091 as Bishop of St David 's , was the author of the standard Life of Saint David .
Father José Joaquin Jimeno ( 1804 - -1856 ) was a Spanish missionary to the Americas .
Thomas James Macnamara PC ( 23 August 1861 -- 3 December 1931 ) was a British teacher , educationalist and radical Liberal politician .
Henry Berkeley , 7th Baron Berkeley ( 26 November 1534- 26 November 1613 ) was an English peer and politician .
Antony Barrington Brown ( 13 July 1927 -- 24 January 2012 ) was a designer , photographer and explorer .
Jocasta Innes ( 21 May 1934 -- 20 April 2013 ) was a British writer , journalist and businesswoman .
Sylvia Agnes Sophia Tait ( 8 January 1917 -- 28 February 2003 ) ( née Wardropper , known as Sylvia Simpson from 1941 to 1956 ) was an English biochemist and endocrinologist .
Joseph Black FRSE FRCPE FPSG ( 16 April 1728 -- 6 December 1799 ) was a Scottish physician and chemist , known for his discoveries of magnesium , latent heat , specific heat , and carbon dioxide .
Zhao Yin ( 趙隱 ) ( died 881 ) , courtesy name Dayin ( 大隱 ) , formally the Count of Tianshui ( 天水伯 ) , was an official of the Chinese dynasty Tang Dynasty , serving as a chancellor during the reigns of Emperor Yizong and Emperor Yizong 's son Emperor Xizong .
William Frederick Eberlein ( June 25 , 1917 , Shawano , Wisconsin -- 1986 , Rochester , New York ) was an American mathematician , specializing in mathematical analysis and mathematical physics .
Girolamo Mei ( 27 May 1519 -- July 1594 ) was an Italian historian and humanist , famous in music history for providing the intellectual impetus to the Florentine Camerata , which attempted to revive ancient Greek music drama .
Frederick Wedmore ( 9 July 1844 -- 25 February 1921 ) was an English art critic and man of letters .
Elias Durnford ( 13 June 1739 -- 21 June 1794 ) was a British army officer and civil engineer who is best known for surveying the town of Pensacola and laying out a city plan based on two public places ( now the Plaza Ferdinand VII and the Seville Square ) .
Edmund Wierciński ( 1899 - 1955 ) was a Polish stage director , actor and educator .
Pietro Bargagli ( 2 August 1844 , Siena -- November 1918 Florence ) was an Italian entomologist who specialised in Coleoptera .
John P. Shanley ( 1915 -- November 28 , 1985 ) was an American journalist , specializing in radio , television and drama , who worked , from 1937 to 1963 , for The New York Times where he won five publisher 's awards .
Hugh McAteer ( Irish : Aodh Mac an tSaoir ; 1917 -- June 1972 ) was a volunteer in , and leader of , the Irish Republican Army .
James Mullin ( 1846 - 1920 ) was born in Cookstown , County Tyrone .
Cyrus Thompson ( 1855 - -1930 ) was a politician and leader of the Populist Party in the U.S. state of North Carolina .
George Leslie Hunter ( 7 August 1877 -- 7 December 1931 ) , was christened simply George Hunter , but he adopted the name Leslie in San Francisco , and Leslie Hunter , became his professional name .
Konrad Eberhard ( 25 November 1768 -- 12 March 1859 ) , a German historical painter , better known as a sculptor , was one of the foremost artists of the so - called Nazarene School , which at one time gathered round Friedrich Overbeck in Rome .
Curry Carter ( April 17 , 1892 - May 1970 ) was a Virginia Democratic politician from Staunton , Virginia .
Hajj Sa'id al - Shawwa ( Arabic : الحـاج سعيد الشوا‎ ) ( 1868 - -October 1930 ) was a Palestinian Arab politician and the first mayor of Gaza , serving from 1906 to 1917 .
Sophus Black ( 2 May 1882 - 22 December 1960 ) was a Danish telegraph manager and art collector .
Jacob van Campen ( 2 February 1596 -- 13 September 1657 ) , was a Dutch artist and architect of the Golden Age .
Sofie Helene Wigert ( née Olsen ; 25 August 1913 -- 9 September 1989 ) was a Norwegian ship owner , Riksmål activist and magazine editor .
Walter I Grenier ( or Walter of Caesarea ) ( died 1154 ) was the Lord of Caesarea in the Kingdom of Jerusalem , succeeding his father Eustace ( died 1123 ) .
Gugsa Welle ( 1875 -- 31 March 1930 ) , also known as Gugsa Wale , Gugsa Wolie and Gugsa Wele , was an army commander and a member of the Royal family of the Ethiopian Empire .
Sir Lancelot Shadwell ( 3 May 1779 -- 10 August 1850 ) was a barrister at Lincoln 's Inn and was Member of Parliament ( MP ) for Ripon from 1826 to 1827 before becoming Vice - Chancellor of England in 1827 .
Indira Devi , born as Indira Raje ( 19 February 1892 -- 6 September 1968 ) , was the consort of Jitendra Narayan , Maharaja of Cooch Behar , and a princess of Baroda State in her own right .
Karen Grude Koht ( 16 November 1871 - - 10 July 1960 ) was a Norwegian educationalist , essayist and feminist pioneer .
Denzil Dean Harber ( 1909 - 1966 ) was an early British Trotskyist leader and later in his life a prominent British ornithologist .
Manga Sewa ( died 1884 ) was a Yalunka paramount chief in Sierra Leone who blew up a magazine and much of Falaba , the capital of Solimana , killing himself , his family and other leaders , rather than let it fall to Samori Toure 's army .
Major General William Alan Beevor Steele CBE ( 4 February 1895 -- 20 January 1966 ) was a general in the Australian Army during the Second World War .
Guiliam or Willem Backereel ( 1570 in Antwerp -- 10 August 1626 in Rome ) , was a Flemish Baroque landscape painter .
Johnson Collins , also referred to as Collin Collins , ( 1847 - 1906 ) was an African - American politician , known for representing Brunswick County in the 1879 - -1880 session of the Virginia General Assembly .
Sir Edward Bayntun ( 1480 -- 27 November ? 1544 ) , of Bromham , Wiltshire , was a gentleman at the court of Henry VIII of England .
Sarah Charlotte , Lady Campbell - Bannerman ( née Bruce ; 1832 -- 30 August 1906 ) was the wife of British Prime Minister Henry Campbell - Bannerman .
Leon Kobrin ( 18731 - -1946 ) was a playwright in Yiddish theater , writer of short stories and novels , and a translator .
Roger Woddis ( 17 May 1917- 16 July 1993 ) was a writer and humorous poet .
Anna Charlotta Schröderheim , née Anna Charlotta von Stapelmohr , also called Ann - Charlotte or Anne - Charlotte , ( 24 September 1754 -- 1 January 1791 ) , was a Swedish noble , wit and salonist , spouse of the politician Elis Schröderheim .
Janet Lees Price ( 19 April 1943 -- 22 May 2012 ) was a British actress with many television credits to her name , including :
Robert Barclay Fox ( 24 July 1873 -- 22 April 1934 ) was a Falmouth businessman and Conservative Party politician in Cornwall .
Reuben Ward Binks ( 1880 , Bolton , Lancashire -- 17 May 1950 , Westmorland ) was a noted English artist in canine portraiture , Lakeland landscapes and wildlife painting .
Sir Edward Charles Dodds , 1st Baronet MVO FRS FRCP ( 13 October 1899 -- 16 December 1973 ) was a British biochemist .
Pavle Bakić ( Serbian : Павле Бакић , Hungarian : Bakith Pál ; ca . 1525 - 20 September 1537 ) was the last Despot of Serbia , he ruled a large territory under the Hungarian crown until his death in 1537 .
Grand Duke Vyacheslav Constantinovich of Russia , ( 13 July 1862 -- 27 February 1879 ) , was a Romanov grand duke and the youngest son of Grand Duke Constantine Nicholaevich of Russia and his wife Grand Duchess Alexandra Iosifovna .
Ernie McMaster ( 7 October 1887 -- 5 December 1971 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Melbourne in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
In 1627 Thomas Tsugi became a martyr as he was burned to death in Nagasaki , Japan -- along with several companions -- for the faith .
William Cooley ( 1783 - -1863 ) was one of the first American settlers , and a regional leader , in what is now known as Broward County , in the US state of Florida .
James M. Dabbs , Jr. ( 1937 - -2004 ) was a social psychologist and professor of psychology at Georgia State University .
Jean Mathieu Seras or Serras ( 16 April 1765 -- 14 April 1815 ) was born in northwest Italy , but adhered to the French Revolution and joined the French army .
William Newport Goodell ( 1908 - -1999 ) was an American artist , craftsman , and educator .
Áed Dibchine mac Senaig ( died 595 ) was a King of Leinster from the Uí Máil branch of the Laigin .
Enda Marren ( 10 December 1934 -- 8 March 2013 ) was a solicitor and a former member of the Irish Council of State .
Wojciech Wiszniewski ( 22 February 1946 in Łódź - 21 February 1981 in Warsaw ) was a Polish filmmaker who mainly directed faux documentaries .
Sir Kenneth James Muir MacKenzie ( 1 May 1882 -- 3 June 1931 ) was a British soldier , lawyer , and judge .
He Zhuguo ( simplified Chinese : 何柱国 ; traditional Chinese : 何柱國 ; pinyin : Hé Zhùguó ; Wade -- Giles : Ho2 Chu4-kuo2 ; 1897 - -1985 ) was a Kuomintang ( KMT ) general from Rong County , Guangxi .
Jane Gomeldon ( née Jane Middleton ; c. 1720 -- 1779 ) was an English writer , poet and adventurer .
Wiyogo Atmodarminto ( 22 November 1922 -- 19 October 2012 ) , popularly known as Bang Wi , was a former Indonesian army general and diplomat .
Remi Schrijnen ( or Richard ; sometimes spelt Remy ; 24 December 1921 -- 27 July 2006 ) was a Belgian volunteer in the German army .
George Pellew ( 1793 - -1866 ) was an English churchman and theologian , Dean of Norwich from 1828 .
McDonald Clarke ( 1798 - -1842 ) was a poet of some fame in New York City in the early part of the 19th century .
Mansel Longworth Dames ( 1850 - -1922 ) was a scholar of oriental and Portuguese languages .
William Rintoul OBE ( 1870 -- 25 August 1936 ) was a British chemist and President of the Faraday Society between 1934 and 1936 .
Aaron Walden ( born at Warsaw about 1835 , died 1912 ) was a Polish Jewish Talmudist , editor , and author .
Gilles Latulippe ( 31 August 1937 -- 23 September 2014 ) was a Québécois actor , comedian and theatre director and manager .
Iris Habib Elmasry ( إيريس حبيب المصري ) was a prominent Coptic Historian ( 1910 - -1994 ) .
James Bloodsworth ( 7 March 1759 -- 21 March 1804 ) was a convict sentenced for the theft of one game cock and two hens at Esher , Surrey .
Edward Adrian Wilson FZS ( `` Uncle Bill '' ) ( 23 July 1872 -- 29 March 1912 ) was an English physician , polar explorer , natural historian , painter and ornithologist .
Enrique Sorrel Contreras ( 3 February 1912 -- 26 October 1991 ) was a Chilean former footballer and manager .
Juanita Martínez ( 1925 - 2001 ) was an Argentine vedette , who starred in revue shows .
Rabindra Kumar Das Gupta ( 11 July 1915 -- 3 February 2009 ) was a Bengali Indian scholar of Bengali and English literature and a social and cultural commentator .
Sir Henry Lewis Guy CBE , FRS , ( 15 June 1887 -- 20 July 1956 ) was a leading British mechanical engineer , notable in particular for his work on steam turbine design .
Rik Battaglia ( byname of Caterino Bertaglia ; 18 February 1927 -- 27 March 2015 ) was an Italian film actor .
Yitskhok Rudashevski ( 10 December 1927 , Vilnius -- 1 October 1943 ) was a young Jewish teenager who lived in the Vilna Ghetto in Lithuania during the 1940s .
Justus Menius ( 13 December 1499 -- 11 August 1558 ) was a German Lutheran pastor , whose name is Latinized from Jost or Just ( i.e. Jodocus ) Menig .
Franklin E. Morales ( 1884 -- 1962 ) was an American Diplomat .
Charles d'Helfer ( 1598 - -1661 ) was a French baroque composer and maître de musique at Soissons Cathedral .
Higaonna Kanryu ( 1849 - 1922 ) was a Ryukyuan karateka well known for his calligraphy and Chinese studies as well as his martial arts .
William Percival Crozier ( 1 August 1879 -- 16 April 1944 ) was a British journalist and editor of the Manchester Guardian from 1932 , when he succeeded Ted Scott , who had died in a sailing accident , until his death in 1944 .
Alexander Muirhead , FRS , ( 26 May 1848 -- 13 December 1920 ) born in East Saltoun , East Lothian , Scotland was an electrical engineer specialising in wireless telegraphy .
Charles Kemball PRSE FRS FRSC FRIC ( 27 March 1923 , Edinburgh -- 4 September 1998 , Tyninghame ) was a Scottish chemist who served as President of the Royal Society of Edinburgh ( 1988 - -91 ) and as President of the Royal Institute of Chemistry ( 1974 - 6 ) .
Blasius of Parma ( Biagio Pelacani da Parma ) ( c. 1365 -- 1416 ) was an Italian philosopher , mathematician and astrologer .
Barry Took ( /ˈbæri ˈtʊk/ , 19 June 1928 -- 31 March 2002 ) was an English writer , television presenter and comedian .
Isobel Wylie Hutchison ( 30 May 1889 - -20 February 1982 ) was a Scottish Arctic traveller and botanist .
Thomas Ballantyne ( 13 August 1829 -- 29 June 1908 ) was a Canadian politician and Speaker of the Ontario Legislature .
Agnes Morley Cleaveland ( 1874 - -1958 ) was an American writer and cattle rancher who lived in New Mexico and California .
Arthur Sperry Pearse ( 1877 - -1956 ) was a botanist and zoologist from the United States .
George Henry Harlow ( 10 June 1787 -- 4 February 1819 ) , was a highly regarded English portrait painter .
Alfred Auguste Nemours ( 13 July 1883 - 17 October 1955 ) was a Haitian General , diplomat and military historian .
H. Price McGrath ( 1813-July 1881 ) was a `` sporting - man '' who opened the first gambling house in the American South , and bred the race horse , Aristides , the winner of the first Kentucky Derby in 1875 .
Delfim Ferreira ( 1888 - 1960 ) was an important Portuguese entrepreneur , born in the town of Riba d'Ave , Vila Nova de Famalição .
Ludwig Mactarian ( 1908 - -1955 ; sometimes spelled ' MacTarian ' ) was an American painter , muralist , and illustrator .
Norm Marshall ( 1918 -- 5 November 2008 ) was a Canadian radio and television broadcaster .
Edward Meetkerke ( 1590 - -1657 ) was an English clergyman and academic , Regius Professor of Hebrew at Oxford from 1620 .
Fei Wuji ( Chinese : 費無極 or 費無忌 ; died 515 BCE ) was a corrupt official of the state of Chu during the reign of King Ping whose persecution of Crown Prince Jian and the family of Wu Zixu led to the defeat and decline of Chu .
Guan Pinghu ( 管平湖 ) ( March 4 , 1897 - - March 28 , 1967 ) , was a leading player of the guqin ( 古琴 ) , a Chinese 7-string bridgeless zither .
Luca Bati ( 1546 -- 17 October 1608 ) was an Italian Baroque composer and music teacher .
Jatri Uld Said Uld Yumani ( Smara , Sahara Spanish , 1921 -- † Rabat , Morocco , 21 December 1993 ) was a Sahrawi politician , professional grazier , procurator of the Cortes Españolas and president of the Djema'a .
Justice Ephraim Akpata died on 8 January 2000 at the age of 72 .
Lieutenant Sir William Earle Welby , 2nd Baronet ( 14 November 1768 -- 3 November 1852 ) was a British land - owner , baronet and Member of Parliament for Grantham from 1807 to 1820 .
Duan Yucai ( Chinese : 段玉裁 ) ( 1735 - -1815 ) , courtesy name Ruoying ( 若膺 ) was a Chinese philologist of the Qing Dynasty .
Hideo Shiraki ( 白木秀雄 ; born 1 January 1933 in Tokyo ; died 31 August 1972 ) was a Japanese jazz drummer and bandleader , best known for his work in the 1950s and 1960s .
Szymon Okolski ( 1580 - -1653 ) , also known as Simon Okolski , was a well - known Polish - Lithuanian historian , theologian , and specialist in heraldry .
Józef Buzek ( 16 November 1873 in Końska - 22 September 1936 in Cieszyn ) was a Polish lawyer , economist , statistician and politician from the region of Cieszyn Silesia .
Bernhard Keil or Keyl ( 1624 -- 3 February 1687 ) was a Danish Baroque painter who became a pupil of Rembrandt .
Richard Swinefield ( or Richard de Swinfield ; died 15 March 1317 ) was a medieval Bishop of Hereford , England .
Mardochée Valabrègue ( 20 September 1852 - 26 March 1934 ) was a French soldier and the successor of Général Alexandre Percin as Chief of Staff for Minister of War Louis André .
Alice Mona Caird ( née Alice Mona Alison , married name Alice Mona Henryson - Caird ) ( 1854 - -1932 ) was a Scottish novelist and essayist whose feminist views sparked controversy in the late 19th century .
Obadiah Grew ( 1607 - -1689 ) was an English nonconformist minister .
Dr Andrew Commins ( 1829 -- 7 January 1916 ) was an Irish lawyer and politician .
Sir Thomas Malory ( c. 1415 - 18 - 14 March , 1471 ) was an English writer , the author or compiler of Le Morte d'Arthur .
Rasamanohari Pulendran ( Tamil : இராசமனோகரி புலேந்திரன் ; 7 February 1949 -- 30 December 2014 ) was a Sri Lankan Tamil politician , Member of Parliament and state minister .
Kostia Vlastos ( 1883 - -1967 ) was a Greek of the diaspora , scion of a family of bankers , whose origins are from the island of Chios .
Gil Heron ( 9 April 1922 -- 27 November 2008 ) was a Jamaican professional footballer .
Sharon Anderson - Gold died from cancer on 26 September 2011 .
Addams Stratton McAllister , Ph.D. ( 24 February 1875 in Covington , Va. , USA -- 26 November 1946 in Clifton Forge , Va. )
Anna Robena Laidlaw or Anna Robena Thomson ( 30 April 1819 -- 29 May 1901 ) was a British pianist .
Hiravijaya ji ( 1526 - -1595 C.E ) ( also known as Muni Hiravijayji and Hiravijay Suri ) was the supreme pontiff of Tapa Gachcha order of Jain Svetambara tradition .
Kwek Hong Png ( Chinese : 郭芳枫 ; pinyin : Guō Fāngfēng ; 1912 -- 8 November 1994 ) was a Singaporean businessperson , known for establishing Hong Leong Group , of which he was also chairperson .
Otto Winter - Hjelm ( 8 October 1837 -- 3 May 1931 ) was a Norwegian musician , conductor , writer , composer and music critic .
Edward Griffin Parker ( November 16 , 1825-March 30 . 1868 ) was a United States lawyer , editor and author .
R. K. Narayan ( 10 October 1906 -- 13 May 2001 ) , full name Rasipuram Krishnaswami Iyer Narayanaswami , was an Indian writer , best known for his works set in the fictional South Indian town of Malgudi .
Commander Francis Spring Rice , 4th Baron Monteagle of Brandon ( 1 October 1852 -- 22 December 1937 ) was an Anglo - Irish peer .
Malik Ishaq ( Urdu : ملک اسحاق ‎ ; 1959 -- 29 July 2015 ) was a Pakistani militant , Sunni supremacist , and leader of globally designated terrorist organization Lashkar - e - Jhangvi ( LeJ ) .
Fred Webber ( 28 April 1883 -- 7 September 1966 ) was an Australian rules footballer in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Jeremiah Basse ( died 1725 ) was a governor of both West and East Jersey .
Jimmy Bharucha , called a ' colossus in Sri Lanka 's broadcasting world ' died in Colombo in June 2005 .
Ibn Abi al - Ashʿath ( Arabic : أحمد بن محمد بن محمد بن أبي الأشعث‎ ; d. 975 CE ) was a Persian physician of medieval Islam .
Gopala Bhatta Goswami ( 1503 - -1578 ) is one of the foremost disciples of the Vaishnava saint , Chaitanya Mahaprabhu , and a leading historical figure in the Gaudiya Vaishnava school of Hinduism .
Berenguer de Cruïlles was bishop of Girona , ( Catalonia ) , ( 1349 - -1362 ) and first President of the Generalitat de Catalunya ( 1359 - -1362 ) in the 14th century .
Sir Arthur Renwick ( 30 May 1837 -- 23 November 1908 ) was an Australian physician , politician and philanthropist .
Tom Tombrello ( 1936 - -2014 ) was a Caltech H. Goddard Professor of Physics .
Henry William Massingham ( 25 May 1860 - 27 August 1924 ) was an English journalist , editor of The Nation from 1907 to 1923 .
Elbeg Nigülesügchi Khan ( 1361 - -1399 ) was a Mongol Khan of the Northern Yuan dynasty based in Mongolia .
Chanda Sahib ( died 14 June 1752 ) was the Mughal Empire 's Sepoy , Divan of the Carnatic , Sipahsalar of the Carnatic , Faujdar and Nawab of the Carnatic between 1749 and 1752 .
Erwin Koopmann ( 1 January 1900 -- 10 November 1943 ) was a highly decorated Oberstleutnant in the Wehrmacht during World War II who commanded several corps .
William Archibald Spooner ( 22 July 1844 -- 29 August 1930 ) was a long - serving Oxford don , notable for absent - mindedness , who was liable to mix - up the syllables in a spoken phrase , with unintentionally comic effect .
Johanna Chandler ( 1820 -- 12 January 1875 ) was a British founder of a home for the paralysed which is now the National Hospital for Neurology and Neurosurgery
Olga Imerslund ( 9 April 1907 -- 23 August 1987 ) was a renowned Norwegian pediatrician best known for her contribution to identification and naming of the Imerslund - Gräsbeck syndrome .
William I. Bertsche ( 1918 - -1998 ) was an American commercial translator .
George P. Oslin ( 1899 -- October 24 , 1996 ) was an American reporter , executive at Western Union and author on the history of telecommunication .
Grace Burrows ( b. 29 June 1893 d. 1980 ? ) was an English violinist , violin teacher and orchestra conductor .
Catherine Norton Sinclair ( 1817 - 1891 ) was an actress - manager who worked with such notable actors as Junius Brutus Booth , Edwin Booth , and Laura Keene .
Errikos Kontarinis ( Greek : Ερρίκος Κονταρίνης,1906 - -1971 ) was a Greek actor and cinematographer .
Van Day Truex ( March 5 , 1904 -- 1979 ) was an American fashion designer .
William Brydone Jack , ( 23 November 1817 -- 23 November 1886 ) , was the University of New Brunswick 's first surveying professor and its second president ( 1861 - 1885 ) .
James Murrell ( c. 1785 -- 16 December 1860 ) , also known as Cunning Murrell , was an English cunning man , or professional folk magician , who spent most of his life in the town of Hadleigh in the eastern English county of Essex .
Sir Charles Francis Noel Murless ( 24 March 1910 -- 9 May 1987 ) was a British racehorse trainer .
Israel Moses Hazan , Sephardic rabbi , Smyrna 1808-Beirut Oct 1862 .
Meskerem Legesse ( 28 September 1986 -- 15 July 2013 ) was an Ethiopian distance runner .
Hans Paus ( born 1656 in Hjartdal -- 18 March 1715 ) was a Norwegian priest and poet .
Philip Babcock Gove ( 1902 - -1972 ) was an American lexicographer who was editor - in - chief of the Webster 's Third New International Dictionary , published in 1961 .
Maurits Pasques de Chavonnes ( 1654 - -8 September 1724 ) was governor of the Cape of Good Hope from 1714 till 1721 .
Thomas Manners - Sutton , 1st Baron Manners PC , KC ( 24 February 1756 -- 31 May 1842 ) , was a British lawyer and politician who served as Lord Chancellor of Ireland from 1807 to 1827 .
Tommaso Lancisi ( 1603 - -1682 ) was an Italian painter , active in a Baroque style .
John Spens , Lord Condie ( 1520?--1573 ) was a Scottish lawyer and judge who became Lord Advocate .
Lily Dampier ( Jan 1859 or 1867 or 1868 -6 February 1915 ) was an Australian actor of stage and screen .
Father Julian Astromov , SJ ( 1820 - 1913 ) was a Russian Catholic priest .
Humphrys Henry Clay Miller , or H.H.C. Miller ( 1845 - -1910 ) , was a Chicago attorney , and civic leader and three - term mayor of Evanston , Illinois .
William Downie ( 1820 - -1893 ) was a Scottish prospector and explorer involved in the gold rushes in California and British Columbia of the mid-19th Century .
Walther Flemming ( 21 April 1843 -- 4 August 1905 ) was a German biologist and a founder of cytogenetics .
Claud Lovelace ( 16 January 1934 -- 7 September 2012 ) was a theoretical physicist noted for his contributions to string theory , specifically , the idea that strings did not have to be restricted to the four dimensions of spacetime .
Vera Poska - Grünthal ( 1898 - -1986 ) was a leading Estonian feminist .
Julian Thoby Stephen ( 1880 -- 20 November 1906 ) , known as the Goth , was the brother of Vanessa Bell and Virginia Woolf , both prominent members of the Bloomsbury Group , and of Adrian Stephen .
William Pitts II ( 1790 - -1840 ) was an English silver - chaser and sculptor .
Thomas Digges ( /dɪɡz/ ; c. 1546 -- 24 August 1595 ) was an English mathematician and astronomer .
John Appleton Brown ( 1844 - -1902 ) was an American painter , born in Newburyport , Mass. He studied in Boston under Benjamin C. Porter , and afterward under Emile Lambinet in Paris .
Niel Gow ( 1727 - -1807 ) was the most famous Scottish fiddler and dancie ( travelling dance instructor and bard ) of the eighteenth century .
John Bekinsau ( 1496?--1559 ) was an English classical scholar and theologian .
Phoui Sananikone ( 1903 -- 4 December 1983 in Paris ) was Prime Minister of the Kingdom of Laos on two occasions in 1950 to 1951 and again from 1958 to 1959 , and also served as Foreign Minister on multiple occasions .
Shin Don ( 신돈 , 1322~1371 ) was a Korean Buddhist monk and scholar during the Goryeo Dynasty ;
Htin Gyi ( Burmese : ထင်ကြီး ; ca . 1916 -- January 2004 ) , also called Tekkatho Htin Gyi or Tin Maung , was a Burmese writer and journalist who spent his life studying Myanmar literature and the press .
John Scott , 1st Earl of Eldon PC KC FRS FSA ( 4 June 1751 -- 13 January 1838 ) was a British barrister and politician .
Retiring from the Army in 1976 , John McGhie continued work as a consultant psychiatrist to government bodies and was appointed President of the Ministry of Defence Army Medical Board , finally retiring in the year of his death , dying at Lenham , Kent , on 12 September 1985 .
Bjarne Jullum ( 25 June 1894 -- 22 September 1973 ) was a Norwegian journalist , cooperativist and politician for the Labour and Communist parties .
Sir Francis Wyndham , 1st Baronet ( c. 1612 -- 15 July 1676 ) of Trent in Somerset ( now in Dorset ) was an English soldier and politician who sat in the House of Commons of England in 1640 .
Valentin Kuzmin ( Russian : Валентин Кузьмин ; 4 January 1941 -- 2008 ) was a Russian butterfly swimmer who won one silver and three gold medals at the European championships in 1962 and 1966 .
William George Woodger ( 12 December 1887 -- 25 January 1979 ) was an Australian army officer , auctioneer , real estate agent , soldier and stock and station agent .
Blessed Maurus Scott ( c. 1579 -- 30 May 1612 ) , born William Scott , was an English lawyer who became a Benedictine monk and priest , serving as a missionary in England during the period of recusancy .
Teófilo Carvalho dos Santos ( 4 September 1906 in Lisbon -- 1986 ) , was a Portuguese politician .
Herman Valentiner ( 8 May 1850 -- 17 September 1913 ) was a Danish mathematician who introduced the Valentiner group in 1889 .
Leofgar was killed by Gruffydd ap Llywelyn on 16 June 1056 at Glasbury - on - Wye during a battle with the Welsh .
Marcel Dupont ( Jupille , 10 October 1917 -- Blegny , 6 March 2008 ) was a Belgian professional road bicycle racer , who finished 5th place in the 1949 Tour de France .
Niccolò Bambini ( 1651 - -1736 ) was an Italian painter of the late - Renaissance and early - Baroque periods .
Puck de Leeuw ( 1953 - 8 February 2002 ) was a Dutch director .
Shailendra Nath Shrivastava ( 26 October 1936 -- 12 February 2006 ) is former Indian politician from Bihar .
Frank Staff ( 15 June 1918 -- 10 May 1971 ) was a South African ballet dancer , choreographer , producer , and company director .
George Cuitt the Elder ( 1743 - -1818 ) was an English painter .
Thurisind ( Latin : Turisindus , died c. 560 ) was king of the Gepids , an East Germanic Gothic people , from c. 548 to 560 .
Alexander Bain Moncrieff CMG ( 22 May 1845 -- 11 April 1928 ) was an Irish - born engineer , active in Australia .
Mario Tamagno ( 19 June 1877 -- 1941 ) was an Italian architect who worked mainly in early 20th - century Siam ( Thailand ) .
Piers Butler , 3rd Viscount Galmoye , otherwise Viscount Galmoy , ( 21 March 1652 -- 18 June 1740 ) was an Anglo - Irish nobleman .
Isaac Hinckley ( 1815 - 1888 ) was a president of the Philadelphia , Wilmington and Baltimore Railroad and the founder of Ridley Park , Pennsylvania .
Ivan Rohach ( Ukrainian : Іван Рогач ) ( 29 May 1913 -- 21 February 1942 ) was a Ukrainian journalist , poet , writer , and political activist born in Velykyi Bereznyi ( Hungarian : Nagyberezna ) , Ung county , Austria - Hungary ( modern - day Ukraine ) .
Stefanos Dimitrios ( Greek : Στέφανος Δημητρίος , 1887 -- 1966 ) was a Greek athlete .
Nils Andersen ( 21 March 1902 -- 7 May 1979 ) was a Norwegian middle and long - distance runner .
Jack de Nijs ( Tjimahi , 18 July 1941 -- Roosendaal , 26 May 1997 ) was a Dutch songwriter , known as a singer under the name of Jack Jersey .
Frederick William Lillywhite ( 13 June 1792 -- 21 August 1854 ) was an English cricketer during the game 's roundarm era .
Leonard Cutler ( 1928 - -2006 ) , also known as Leonard S. Cutler , was a pioneer and authority on ultra - precise timekeeping devices and standards , and was well known for his work with quantum - mechanical effects .
Peter Paul Pugin ( 1851 -- March 1904 ) was an English architect , son of Augustus Welby Pugin by his third wife Jane Knill .
Sir Edwin Hardy Amies , KCVO ( 17 July 1909 -- 5 March 2003 ) , known as Hardy Amies , was an English fashion designer , founder of the Hardy Amies label and best known for his official title as dressmaker for Queen Elizabeth II , from her accession to the throne 1952 until his retirement in 1989 .
Henri François Lambert ( 3 June 1760 -- 7 September 1796 ) was a brigadier general of the French revolutionary army .
Lazaros Sochos ( Greek : Λάζαρος Σώχος ; 1862 - 1911 ) was a Greek sculptor .
Sophie Amalie Lindenov , Baroness of Lindenborg ( 4 July 1649 -- 1688 ) was a Danish noblewoman and landowner .

The Pentium Dual - Core brand was used for mainstream x86-architecture microprocessors from Intel from 2006 to 2009 when it was renamed to Pentium .

DePatie - Freleng Enterprises ( also known as Mirisch - Geoffrey - DePatie Freleng Productions when involved with the Mirisch brothers and Geoffrey Productions ; and DFE Films ) was an American animation production company , active from 1963 to 1981 .
The Riograndense Republic , often called Piratini Republic ( Portuguese : República Rio - Grandense or República do Piratini ) , was a de facto state that existed between September 11 , 1836 and March 1 , 1845 roughly coinciding with the present state of Rio Grande do Sul , in Brazil .
On 3 July 2006 , Meadow Fresh NZ Ltd , Top Hat Convenience Foods Ltd , and Goodman Fielder New Zealand Ltd amalgamated to become Goodman Fielder New Zealand Ltd.
Lucent was merged with Alcatel SA of France in a merger of equals on December 1 , 2006 , forming Alcatel - Lucent .
Beginning in February 1946 , the Red Army , along with the Soviet Navy , embodied the main component of the Soviet Armed Forces ; taking the official name of `` Soviet Army '' ( Russian : Советская Армия ( СА)/Sovetskaya Armija ) , until its dissolution in December 1991 .
The Khanate of Kokand ( Uzbek : Qo'qon Xonligi , Persian : خانات خوقند‎‎ ) was a Central Asian state that existed from 1709 - -1876 within the territory of modern Kyrgyzstan , eastern Uzbekistan and Tajikistan , and southeastern Kazakhstan .
The General Popular Radical Union ( Greek : Γενική Λαϊκή Ριζοσπαστική Ένωσις ) was a coalition of three Greek political parties for the elections of 1936 .
The Republic of San Marco ( Italian : Repubblica di San Marco ) , an Italian revolutionary state , existed for 17 months in 1848 - -1849 .
Majola was a French producer of engines and automobiles , established in 1908 and producing automobiles from 1911 till 1928 .
The Han Zhao ( simplified Chinese : 汉赵 ; traditional Chinese : 漢趙 ; pinyin : Hànzhào ; 304 - -329 ) , or Former Zhao , or Northern Han ( 北漢 ) , was a Southern Xiongnu state during Sixteen Kingdoms period coeval with the Chinese Jin Dynasty ( 265 - 420 ) .
Merkur ( German pronunciation : ( mɛʁˈkuːɐ̯ ) ) , Mercury ) was a short - lived automobile brand sold by the Lincoln - Mercury division of Ford Motor Company from 1985 to 1989 .
The Kingdom of Seville ( Spanish : Reino de Sevilla ) was a territorial jurisdiction of the Crown of Castile from the time it was won from Muslim rule in 1248 during the Reconquista until Javier de Burgos ' provincial division of Spain in 1833 .
The Celtic Warriors were a regional rugby union team from Wales , who played in the Celtic League and Heineken Cup between 2003 and 2004 following a merger between Welsh clubs Pontypridd RFC and Bridgend RFC at the inception of Regional Rugby in Wales .
The Territory of the Saar Basin ( German : Saarbeckengebiet ; French : Le Territoire du Bassin de la Sarre ) was a region of Germany occupied and governed by the United Kingdom and France from 1920 to 1935 under a League of Nations mandate .
FC Swarovski Tirol was an Austrian association football club from 1986 - -1992 , based in Innsbruck , Tirol , Austria .
On April 2 , 2015 , it was announced that Sony Computer Entertainment had acquired OnLive 's patents , and that all OnLive services would be discontinued on April 30 , 2015 .
The Le Cabri was a French automobile manufactured from 1924 to 1925 .
The Baltimore Marylands were a short - lived professional baseball team that existed in the 1873 National Association season .
The Province of East Jersey , along with the Province of West Jersey , between 1674 and 1702 in accordance with the Quintipartite Deed were two distinct political divisions of the Province of New Jersey , which became the U.S. state of New Jersey .

Emigi ( Persian : اميگي‎ , also Romanized as Emīgī ; also known as Chūkhūn ) is a village in Jakdan Rural District , in the Central District of Bashagard County , Hormozgan Province , Iran .
Seljublje ( Cyrillic : Сељубље ) is a village in the municipality of Kalesija , Bosnia and Herzegovina .
Nadolice Wielkie ( nadɔˈlit͡sɛ ˈvjɛlkʲɛ ) ( German : Groß Nädlitz ) is a village in the administrative district of Gmina Czernica , within Wrocław County , Lower Silesian Voivodeship , in south - western Poland .
Krasiatychi ( Ukrainian : Красятичі , Russian : Красятичи ) , also spelled Krasyatychi , is an urban - type settlement in Kiev Oblast ( province ) of Ukraine .
Maddikera is a mandal and village in Kurnool district of Andhra Pradesh , India .
L'Escarène is an ancient commune in the Alpes - Maritimes department in southeastern France .
Bárcena Mayor is a village nestled in the mountains of Cantabria , Spain in the municipality of Los Tojos , and is the only residential village within Saja Reservation within the Saja and Nansa valleys community .
Porte des Morts , also known as Porte des Mortes , the Door of Death , and Death 's Door is a strait linking Lake Michigan and Green Bay between the northern tip of the peninsula of Door County , Wisconsin and a group of islands historically known as the Potawatomi Islands and dominated by Washington Island .
Tazeh Kand - e Masqaran ( Persian : تازه كندمسقران‎ , also Romanized as Tāzeh Kand - e Masqarān and Tāzeh Kand Masqarān ; also known as Tazakend , Tāzeh Kand , and Tazeh Kand Masfaran ) is a village in Azghan Rural District , in the Central District of Ahar County , East Azerbaijan Province , Iran .
Xima ( Chinese : 郄马镇 ) is a township - level division of Luancheng County , Shijiazhuang , Hebei , China .
The C.A. Rownd Round Barn is an historic structure located south of Cedar Falls , Iowa in Black Hawk County .
Greenwood Reservoir is a large , 1,073-acre ( 4.34 km2 ) impoundment located in Michigan 's Upper Peninsula .
The General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon is a single - engine multirole fighter aircraft originally developed by General Dynamics ( now Lockheed Martin ) for the United States Air Force ( USAF ) .
Shalimar - class ferry is a series of three service watercraft being built by Shalimar Works ( 1980 ) Ltd , Kolkata for the Indian Navy .
The Ramblin ' Wreck from Georgia Tech is the 1930 Ford Model A Sport coupe that serves as the official mascot of the student body at the Georgia Institute of Technology .

The DECSYSTEM-20 was a 36-bit Digital Equipment Corporation PDP-10 mainframe computer running the TOPS-20 operating system ( products introduced in 1977 ) .

Windows XP ( codenamed Whistler ) is a personal computer operating system that was produced by Microsoft as part of the Windows NT family of operating systems .
The Walther P38 ( also known as a Pistole 38 ) is a 9 mm semi - automatic pistol that was developed by Walther arms as the service pistol of the Wehrmacht shortly before World War II . It was intended to replace the costly Luger P08 , the production of which was scheduled to end in 1942 .
The Denel 35 mm Dual Purpose Gun ( 35DPG ) is a close - in weapon system ( CIWS ) for warships built in South Africa by Denel Land Systems .
The PlayStation Vita ( officially abbreviated PS Vita ) is a handheld game console manufactured and marketed by Sony Computer Entertainment .

The 80th Regiment of Foot ( Staffordshire Volunteers ) was an infantry regiment of the British Army , created in 1793 and amalgamated into The South Staffordshire Regiment in 1881 .

The Pecatonica River is a tributary of the Rock River , 194 miles ( 312 km ) long , in southern Wisconsin and northern Illinois in the United States .
The mouth of the Orinoco at the Atlantic Ocean was documented by Columbus on 1 August 1498 , during his third voyage .
The Bundara River rises east of Mount Hotham and Mount Loch in the Australian Alps in the Alpine National Park at an elevation of 1,420 m ( 4,659 ft ) , and flows into the Big River about 2 kilometres ( 1.2 mi ) north of Anglers Rest .
Surxondaryo River , also Surkhandarya River , Surxon River , Surkhan River , Surkhan Darya ( darya means `` river '' ) is a river in Uzbekistan , a right tributary of the Amu Darya .
The Kadalundi River drains an area of 1274 km² and has a length of 120 km . The Kadalundi Bird Sanctuary spreads over a cluster of islands where the Kadalundipuzha River flows into the Arabian Sea .
The Kleine Emme is a river of the canton of Lucerne , Switzerland , a left tributary of the Reuss extending for 58 km , draining a basin of 477 km² .
Ahr is a river in Germany , a left tributary of the Rhine .
In mathematics , Landau 's function g(n ) , named after Edmund Landau , is defined for every natural number n to be the largest order of an element of the symmetric group Sn .
Aegirine was named after Ægir , the Teutonic god of the sea .
The Coulomb barrier , named after Coulomb 's law , which is named after physicist Charles - Augustin de Coulomb ( 1736 - -1806 ) , is the energy barrier due to electrostatic interaction that two nuclei need to overcome so they can get close enough to undergo a nuclear reaction .
Moser 's worm problem is an unsolved problem in geometry formulated by the Austrian - Canadian mathematician Leo Moser in 1966 .
Blödite was first described in 1821 for an occurrence in a salt deposit in Ischler Salzberg , Bad Ischl , Gmunden , Austria and named for German mineralogist and chemist Karl August Blöde ( 1773 - -1820 ) .
Tyndallization is a process dating from the nineteenth century for sterilizing substances , usually food , named after its inventor , scientist John Tyndall .
The Open and Free Technology Community ( OFTC ) is an IRC network that provides collaboration services to members of the free software community in any part of the world .
In mathematics , Hilbert 's syzygy theorem is a result of commutative algebra , first proved by David Hilbert ( 1890 ) in connection with the syzygy ( relation ) problem of invariant theory .
The Sibelius Society of Finland ( Finnish : Sibelius - Seura ry , Swedish : Sibelius - Samfundet rf ) is a society in Finland dedicated to the music of the Finnish composer Jean Sibelius .
Martensite , named after the German metallurgist Adolf Martens ( 1850 - -1914 ) , most commonly refers to a very hard form of steel crystalline structure , but it can also refer to any crystal structure that is formed by diffusionless transformation .
